WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.280
Hi, my name is Julia Silgi and I'm excited to talk to you about a workshop that I'm teaching

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:18.799
at this year's PositConf in Chicago about how to deploy and maintain models with vetiver.

00:00:18.799 --> 00:00:25.760
It turns out that lots of data scientists and other kinds of data practitioners know

00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:30.920
how to approach training a model, a machine learning model or a statistical model.

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:32.400
There's lots of books about this.

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:35.320
This is something that they teach in classes at school.

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:41.599
However, when it comes time to deploy that model and maintain that model in the long

00:00:41.599 --> 00:00:47.360
run as it interacts with the real world, there's a lot more uncertainty and it can be pretty

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:53.040
daunting to figure out where to start, what are the tasks that are involved.

00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:57.840
The term that is typically used for those kinds of tasks is MLOps, which stands for

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:00.520
Machine Learning Operations.

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:07.360
I'll be honest, there's a lot of hype around that term, around tooling in the MLOps space.

00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:11.040
What we're going to do in this workshop is we are going to step back from the hype and

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:18.360
focus on the substantive, concrete tasks that you need to know how to do in order to make

00:01:18.360 --> 00:01:23.120
sure you are deploying and maintaining your model in a reliable way.

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:30.599
We're going to focus on how to version, how to deploy and how to monitor models.

00:01:30.599 --> 00:01:33.559
We're going to use the vetiver framework for this.

00:01:33.559 --> 00:01:38.559
So vetiver is a framework for MLOps tasks in R and Python.

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:43.599
And that means this workshop is going to be a little unique in that you can choose your

00:01:43.599 --> 00:01:45.199
own adventure.

00:01:45.199 --> 00:01:51.040
You can come to this workshop with a model or a type of model that you want to learn

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:53.660
how to deploy and maintain.

00:01:53.660 --> 00:01:58.839
You can choose to work in R or Python or a little bit of both, I guess, if that's what

00:01:58.839 --> 00:02:00.839
you want to do.

00:02:00.839 --> 00:02:06.400
If I were to sum up one reason why I think you should think about taking this workshop,

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:14.440
I would say if you are someone who develops models as part of your role, you are someone

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:21.479
who trains a model, who tunes a model's hyperparameters, who evaluates that model to understand how

00:02:21.479 --> 00:02:26.080
well is it performing, how reliable and appropriate it is to this use case.

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:30.960
If that's you, then you can deploy that model.

00:02:30.960 --> 00:02:37.479
And in fact, you probably should be the one to deploy and maintain that model in the long

00:02:37.479 --> 00:02:42.399
run because of the depth of knowledge that you have about how that model works, the constraints

00:02:42.399 --> 00:02:43.600
around it.

00:02:43.759 --> 00:02:52.320
So you can learn how to get your model off your laptop and out into the wide world out

00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:56.479
there integrated into your organization's infrastructure.

00:02:56.479 --> 00:02:58.639
I look forward to seeing you at the workshop.

